Member 1 – Introduction & Evolution Timeline

Good morning everyone. Today we are presenting the topic From Paper Shopping to E-Commerce. This infographic explains the journey of shopping from traditional methods to modern digital platforms. In the early days, especially in the 1990s, people used paper catalogs, printed advertisements, and physical stores to buy products. Customers had to spend time traveling to shops, checking product availability, comparing prices manually, and standing in billing queues. Shopping required more time and effort. In the late 1990s, the internet introduced Web 1.0 stores. These were the first online stores where people could view products and place simple orders. Although websites were basic, they opened the door for digital commerce. In the 2000s, online marketplaces became popular because they allowed multiple sellers to sell products on one platform, giving customers more choices and better prices. During the 2010s, smartphones and mobile apps completely changed shopping habits. People could order products anytime and anywhere with just a few clicks. In the 2020s, shopping became smarter with social media promotions, influencer marketing, and artificial intelligence. AI now helps customers with recommendations, chat support, and personalized offers. This timeline clearly shows how technology transformed shopping into a faster, easier, and more convenient experience.

Member 2 – Key Statistics

Now let us look at some key statistics shown in the infographic. These numbers help us understand the scale of global e-commerce in 2026. First, global e-commerce sales reached 6.88 trillion dollars, which is an enormous value. This means businesses around the world are earning huge revenue through online platforms. Second, there are 2.86 billion online shoppers worldwide. This shows that a large percentage of the world’s population now depends on online shopping for daily needs, electronics, clothing, and many other products. Third, e-commerce contributes 21.1% of total retail sales. This means more than one out of every five retail purchases happens online. Finally, 59% of online sales happen through mobile devices such as smartphones and tablets. This highlights the importance of mobile-friendly apps and websites. These statistics clearly prove that e-commerce has become a major part of the global economy. It is creating jobs, increasing business opportunities, and changing the way customers interact with markets. The future of shopping will continue to depend heavily on digital platforms.

Member 3 – Global Sales Growth (2015–2026)

This bar graph shows the growth of global e-commerce sales from 2015 to 2026. In 2015, online shopping sales were much lower because many people still preferred traditional stores. At that time, digital payments and delivery systems were still improving. However, as internet speed increased and smartphones became affordable, more customers started using e-commerce websites and apps. From 2016 to 2019, sales grew steadily every year. Companies improved customer service by offering discounts, free delivery, easy returns, and secure payment options. This built trust among users. The biggest growth happened after 2020, when online shopping became essential for convenience and safety. Many businesses that only operated offline also moved online to survive in the competitive market. By 2026, sales reached their highest point, close to 7 trillion dollars. This graph clearly shows that e-commerce is one of the fastest-growing industries in the world. It also teaches businesses that digital transformation is necessary to remain successful. Customers now expect speed, convenience, and better service, which online platforms provide effectively.

Member 4 – Shopping Channels & Product Categories

This section explains where people shop online and what they prefer to buy. According to the infographic, 59% of online purchases happen through mobile phones. Mobile shopping is popular because apps are easy to use, save time, and allow customers to shop from anywhere. Features like one-click payment, notifications, and live tracking make mobile shopping even better. 28% of shopping happens through desktops and laptops, especially for office users or customers who prefer larger screens for comparing products. 8% of shopping comes through social media platforms, where users discover products through advertisements, live selling, and influencer promotions. The remaining 5% comes from other channels. The infographic also highlights top product categories. Fashion is the highest at 23%, showing that clothes, shoes, and accessories are highly demanded online. Electronics account for 21%, including mobiles, laptops, and gadgets. Grocery contributes 18%, proving that even daily essentials are now bought online. Beauty, home products, and other categories also hold significant shares. This shows that e-commerce is not limited to luxury items—it supports all types of consumer needs in modern life.

Member 5 – Regional Market Share & Payment Methods

This section focuses on global market share and payment methods used in e-commerce. The Asia-Pacific region leads with 45% of the global e-commerce market. This is mainly because of large populations, growing internet access, and rapid digital adoption in countries like India and China. These nations have millions of online buyers and sellers. North America holds 25%, supported by advanced technology, strong logistics systems, and trusted online brands. Western Europe has 18%, while Latin America and the rest of the world make up smaller shares. This proves that online shopping is expanding across every region. The infographic also explains payment methods. Digital wallets are the most preferred option because they are quick, secure, and easy to use. Customers can pay instantly using mobile apps. Credit and debit cards are the second most common method, especially for international purchases. Bank transfers are also used, while Buy Now Pay Later services are growing because they allow customers to purchase products in installments. Safe and flexible payment methods are one of the main reasons for e-commerce success. They reduce risk and improve customer confidence.

Member 6 – How People Shop Today & Conclusion

The final section shows current shopping behavior and future trends. In 2026, there are 1.65 billion smartphone shoppers, proving that mobile commerce is dominating the market. Smartphones have become the easiest tool for browsing, ordering, paying, and tracking products. Social commerce sales have reached 1.63 trillion dollars, which means people are increasingly buying products directly through social media platforms. Around 70% of shoppers in the United States prefer apps over websites because apps provide faster loading, better offers, and smoother experiences. Another interesting fact is that 58% of customers purchase products because of influencer recommendations. This shows the strong power of digital marketing and social media trust. India is one of the fastest-growing e-commerce markets with 14.1% CAGR, showing huge potential for future business growth. The AI market in e-commerce has reached 9.9 billion dollars, showing how technology is improving recommendations, customer support, fraud detection, and demand forecasting. In conclusion, shopping today is smart, fast, and customer-friendly. Technology has changed shopping from paper catalogs to personalized digital experiences. In the future, e-commerce will continue to grow with AI, automation, and better customer experiences.
